    text: 'The traditional five-day workweek, established during the industrial era, is being re-evaluated by companies worldwide. Recent corporate trials across several countries have tested the feasibility of a four-day workweek without any reduction in employee pay. The main philosophy behind this experiment is the concept of 100-80-100: receiving 100% of the salary for 80% of the hours, provided that 100% of the normal productivity is maintained.\n\nThe results of these trials have been overwhelmingly positive for both employers and workers. Companies report that employee burnout levels have decreased dramatically, while mental health and job satisfaction ratings have soared. Interestingly, productivity did not drop; in fact, many organizations recorded slight increases in output. Employees became more focused, cut down on unnecessary meetings, and managed their time more efficiently in order to enjoy their three-day weekends.\n\nDespite the clear benefits, transitioning to a shorter workweek requires careful planning. Certain industries, such as healthcare, customer support, and manufacturing, operate on continuous schedules that make reduced hours difficult to coordinate. Nevertheless, the successful trials suggest that flexible work structures are no longer just a luxury, but a sustainable model for the modern knowledge economy.',
