    text: 'No other running event captures the spirit of endurance quite like the marathon. The race traces its roots back to the legendary run of Pheidippides, a Greek soldier who ran from the battlefield of Marathon to Athens to deliver news of a military victory. According to historical lore, after shouting "We have won!", he collapsed and died. When the modern Olympic Games were revived in Athens in 1896, organizers created a long-distance race to honor this legendary feat.\n\nIn the early Olympics, the distance of the marathon varied slightly. It was not until the 1908 London Games that the distance was officially standardized at 42.195 kilometers (26.2 miles). The race was set so it could start at Windsor Castle and finish directly in front of the Royal Box at the stadium. This specific distance has remained the international standard ever since, challenging millions of amateur and elite athletes annually.\n\nToday, the marathon represents the ultimate test of human willpower. Winning the Olympic marathon is considered one of the highest achievements in sports. The event is traditionally held on the final day of the Olympic Games, with the closing ceremony featuring the medal presentation for the marathon champions, symbolizing the triumph of human spirit and physical endurance.',
